## Social and Cultural Changes

### Education and Intellectual Life

Under Mao, especially during the Cultural Revolution, education was severely disrupted, with schools closed and intellectuals persecuted. After Mao's death, entrance examinations for universities were reinstated in 1977, signaling a revival of formal education and intellectual life. The CCP also sent students abroad to study, facilitating the transfer of knowledge and technology ([Acienciala.ku.edu](https://acienciala.ku.edu/communistnationssince1917/ch10.html); [Fsmitha.com](http://www.fsmitha.com/h2/ch32prc.html)).

### Cultural Liberalization

The post-Mao era saw a relaxation of ideological control over art and literature. Chinese writers and artists began to explore themes of victimization and suffering from the Cultural Revolution, breaking away from socialist realism. Foreign cultural influences, previously condemned, entered China, enriching its cultural landscape ([Oxford Bibliographies](https://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780199920082/obo-9780199920082-0017.xml)).

### Social Issues

Despite economic progress, China faced social challenges, including:

- **Rural-Urban Divide:** Economic reforms favored urban coastal regions, leaving rural areas behind.
- **Migrant Labor:** Large-scale migration to cities created social tensions.
- **Human Rights:** Issues such as the one-child policy, labor conditions, and censorship persisted ([Brainly.com, 2018](https://brainly.com/question/10706936)).

